<div id="review_3643058592" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3643058592" />
    <a title="Sofia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/114413220-sofia"><img alt="Sofia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1607792875p2/114413220.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3643058592?book_show_action=true">Dec 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sofia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sofia" href="/user/show/114413220-sofia">Sofia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140449266" href="/book/show/7126.The_Count_of_Monte_Cristo">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3643058592" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6177665201380238536"><b>Part 1 of Sofia&apos;s Plan:</b> <i>The Count of Monte Cristo</i><br/><br/>I have developed a plan to gain more brain cells by reading classic literature. If successful, I will be an intellectual by next year. Wish me luck! <br/><br/>___<br/><br/><br/>After being arrested on trumped-up charges forged by his enemies, Edmond Dantes is imprisoned for fourteen years. With only his furious thoughts and an old abbe to keep him company, he slowly and carefully plots his revenge. When he finally escapes from prison, he finds a lost fortune on the isle o</span>
  <span id="freeText6177665201380238536" style="display:none"><b>Part 1 of Sofia's Plan:</b> <i>The Count of Monte Cristo</i><br><br>I have developed a plan to gain more brain cells by reading classic literature. If successful, I will be an intellectual by next year. Wish me luck! <br><br>___<br><br><br>After being arrested on trumped-up charges forged by his enemies, Edmond Dantes is imprisoned for fourteen years. With only his furious thoughts and an old abbe to keep him company, he slowly and carefully plots his revenge. When he finally escapes from prison, he finds a lost fortune on the isle of Monte Cristo and creates an entirely new persona for himself--The Count of Monte Cristo, a cunning, reclusive, and mysterious man. He has one goal: exacting revenge on his enemies. <br><br><br>This sounds spooky, but it's actually quite funny. Mostly because of the many French nobles who live to cause drama. If every Madame and Monsieur in this book simply stopped being unnecessarily dramatic, half of the plot would vanish. But I don't mind, because it was amusing. <br><br><br>The Count is no better than the rest, as he has a strange penchant for making things more important than they actually are. After one of his schemes goes wrong, Albert--the son of the unfortunate Count imprisoned--tries to throw a glove at him in the theater. I was very incredulous while reading this, because Monte Cristo actually sneaks into Albert's house with a pistol and tries to kill him. Because of the glove. It was only after laughing for quite a while that I learned that throwing a glove at someone means you're challenging them to a duel. Still, it would look ridiculous. Imagine tossing your glove at some random Count. I would laugh. That's not intimidating at all. <br><br><br>And then, the few times the Count actually speaks, he's just so hilarious and I don't even know why. <br><br><blockquote>
  <i>"He replied that it was not a natural death, and that it could only be attributed to...to poison."<br>"Really!" said Monte Cristo with a slight cough, "did you really hear that?</i>
</blockquote><br><br>Edmond Dantes, you are a horrible person, but we love you anyway. <br><br><br>And then, of course, they feel the need to be even more dramatic. Here's some backstory. One of the other Counts, Edmond's old enemy, is begging him to reveal who he really is--he didn't recognize Edmond from their sailing days. So Dantes takes off his jacket and puts on some old sailing clothes that conveniently happen to be right next to him. And the other Count is so shocked, it's hilarious. He starts screaming about how Edmond's here and Edmond's back from the dead. Because apparently changing your clothes is enough to make you a completely different person. Don't ask me. <br><br><br>I didn't like everything about this book, however. There were some <i>really</i> problematic things that were going on. I know that this is old and dated, but some themes were taken to extremes. Like the elephant in the room here. Haydee. The slave. <br><br>I'm not going to go into much detail because of ✨spoilers,✨ but the creepometer was going crazy.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1607116253ra/30472217.gif" alt="Creepin GIF - CreepOMeter Danger - Discover &amp; Share GIFs" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><br>Haydee is a slave who belongs to Monte Cristo. She's oddly dedicated to him and makes these very cringy and very problematic declarations of love: <br><br><blockquote>
  <i>"You are good, you are great, my lord," said Haydee, kissing Monte Cristo's hand. "I am very happy to belong to you.</i>
</blockquote><br><br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1607116253ra/30472218.gif" alt="What The Heck GIFs | Tenor" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br><br>No. Just... no. And then, well... I can't really say anything without spoiling the book, but there's a romance. And this girl calls Monte Cristo her "second father." There is just so much that's wrong with this entire subplot. I can't really go into it without opening another can of worms, but I think you can come to your own conclusions. <br><br><br>The character development is really the only other big problem with this book. It's very sudden and doesn't make a whole lot of sense. Edmond changes from a sweet, caring, and buoyant young man into a brooding, evil, and merciless one very suddenly. I wanted to see his descent into madness, but that wasn't really shown, even in the prison, where he was still kind-hearted. <br><br><br>The writing... well, it wasn't anything special. I would even call it mediocre. The same descriptions were used repeatedly: "turned pale," "exclaimed," etc. It was repetitive and rather dull, but it did the job. <br><br><br><b>Did I gain brain cells?</b><br><br>Probably. I mean, I know how to break out of prison now, so... <br><br><br><br>4 stars<br><br><br><br>____<br><br>Part 2: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3671460931?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=1" rel="nofollow noopener">Of Mice and Men</a><br>Part 3: <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3679512629" rel="nofollow noopener">Rebecca</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="6177665201380238536" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


